```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{forest}
\usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}

\begin{document}

\begin{forest}
  for tree={
    grow'=0,
    l sep=15mm,
    s sep=20mm,
    edge={Stealth-},
    align=center,
    parent anchor=south,
    child anchor=north,
    fit=band,
  }
  [\textbf{Summation Methods}
    [Sequential
      [N\"{o}rlund]
      [Euler]
    ]
    [Functional
      [Abelian means]
      [Lambert]
      [Mittag-Leffler]
    ]
    [Abel]
    [weak Borel]
    [strong Borel]
  ]
\end{forest}

\end{document}
```

This code uses the `forest` package to draw the tree structure. The `for tree` option sets the default properties for each node in the tree, such as the direction of growth (`grow'=0`), the separation between levels (`l sep` and `s sep`), the type of arrow used for edges (`edge={Stealth-}`), and the alignment of nodes (`align=center`). The `parent anchor` and `child anchor` options ensure that the edges connect correctly.

The `\textbf{Summation Methods}` text is used to label the root of the tree. The `[Sequential]`, `[Functional]`, etc., are the branches of the tree, and the nodes within these branches are labeled accordingly. The arrows between nodes indicate the relationships described in the caption.

